			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-1322" title="Photo of Shauntay Grant (by Raul Rincon)" src="http://www.justonemorebook.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/sgrant09.jpg" alt="Photo of Shauntay Grant (by Raul Rincon)" />While her book <a title="Up Home" href="http://www.nimbus.ns.ca/Store/CatalogItem/tabid/904/ProductID/5347/Default.aspx" target="_blank">Up Home</a> may be set in the one of Canada&#8217;s most important black communities, author <a title="Shauntay Grant" href="http://www.writers.ns.ca/Writers/sgrant.html" target="_blank">Shauntay Grant</a>&#8216;s story is universal. As noted in the jacket flap, the book celebrates growing up and remembering our roots.</p>
<p>On this edition of <a title="Just One More Book!! children's book podcast" href="http://www.justonemorebook.com/" target="_blank">Just One More Book!!</a>, Mark speaks with Shauntay Grant about turning a spoken word performance piece into a children&#8217;s book, the role of verse in children&#8217;s literature and sharing the experience of growing up.</p>
<p><em>Photo of Shauntay Grant by Raul Rincon</em>.</p>
