		<title>A Capital Lament: The End of an Era</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/JustOneMoreBook/~3/IP8SvnNuTPA/</link>
		<comments>http://justonemorebook.com/2009/09/11/a-capital-lament-the-end-of-an-era/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 11 Sep 2009 06:00:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>justonemorebook@gmail.com (Mark Blevis and Andrea Ross)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Canadian]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News and Notes]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Podcast]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Poetry Friday]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Rhyming]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[all in a day]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[brent bambury]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[CBC]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[go!]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Ottawa]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[poem]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.justonemorebook.com/?p=1313</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[It&#8217;s Poetry Friday and, since I&#8217;ve been pushed beyond my limits by members of the book industry&#8217;s dark side, we present a poem I wrote back in the spring of 2005 to lament the loss of CBC Ottawa&#8217;s much loved afternoon host, Brent Bambury. I&#8217;ve loved doing Just One More Book!! and it will be [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/electricsky/3820480403/in/photostream/"><img class="alignright" src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2424/3820480403_df299c88e9_m.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a>It&#8217;s Poetry Friday and, since I&#8217;ve been pushed beyond my limits by members of the book industry&#8217;s dark side, we present a poem I wrote back in the spring of 2005 to lament the loss of CBC Ottawa&#8217;s much loved afternoon host, <a title="Brent Bambury" href="http://www.cbc.ca/go/host.html" target="_blank">Brent Bambury</a>.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve loved doing Just One More Book!! and it will be sad to turn my back on it.</p>
<p>While I&#8217;m reflecting on the future of what has been a huge part of our family, every single day for more than three years, I thought it was appropriate to share this era-ending poem (read by its recipient, Brent Bambury).</p>
<p><strong>A Capital Lament</strong> &#8212; by Andrea Ross, May 2005.</p>
<p>That April day, infused by May, seemed clearly heaven sent,<br />
<a title="The Gomery Commission, 2005" href="http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&amp;Params=M1ARTM0012755" target="_blank">The Gomery mess</a> couldn&#8217;t bug us less &#8212; we&#8217;re listening to Brent!<br />
<a title="Election of Pope Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, April 19, 2005" href="http://www.smokemachines.net/papal-smoke.shtml" target="_blank">Big news from Rome</a>, then Pow! our own calamitous event,<br />
We&#8217;d lost our man, and thus began our <a href="http://www.ottawatourism.ca/en/discoverottawa/ottawa-experiences/capital" target="_blank">Capital</a> Lament.</p>
<p>In two aught two, when Brent was new, our cautious ears we lent,<br />
But soon his pace, words, voice and taste led to enravishment.<br />
Who know his stint would be a glint? That <em><a href="http://www.cbc.ca/go/" target="_blank">Go!</a></em> would lead to went?<br />
And we&#8217;d be left a town bereft, despite all blandishments.</p>
<p><a title="Robert Fontaine" href="http://www.penumbrapress.com/book.php?id=274" target="_blank">Robert Fontaine</a>, comedien, now who will he torment?<br />
Will <a href="http://www.cbc.ca/programguide/personality/lucy_van_oldenbarneveld" target="_blank">Lucy</a> sob? Or grab the job? To whom will <a href="http://www.cbc.ca/allinaday/laurence.html" target="_blank">Laurence</a> vent?<br />
We&#8217;re sure of this, we&#8217;ll sorely miss our host omniloquent.<br />
You&#8217;re lane to fame is <a href="http://www.seetorontonow.com/Visitor/Explore.aspx" target="_blank">Hog Town</a>&#8216;s gain. Best luck and Thank you, Brent.</p>
<p><em>Read Mark&#8217;s post about Just One More Book!! as a member of our family: </em><a title="The baby, the bathwater, or both?" href="http://www.markblevis.com/the-baby-the-bathwater-or-both/" target="_blank"><em>The baby, the bathwater, or both?</em></a></p>
<div class="feedflare">
<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/JustOneMoreBook?a=IP8SvnNuTPA:rikQYAKkN20:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/JustOneMoreBook?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/JustOneMoreBook?a=IP8SvnNuTPA:rikQYAKkN20:63t7Ie-LG7Y"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/JustOneMoreBook?d=63t7Ie-LG7Y" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/JustOneMoreBook?a=IP8SvnNuTPA:rikQYAKkN20:YwkR-u9nhCs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/JustOneMoreBook?d=YwkR-u9nhCs" border="0"></img></a>
</div>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://justonemorebook.com/2009/09/11/a-capital-lament-the-end-of-an-era/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>31</slash:comments>

			<itunes:keywords>all in a day,brent bambury,CBC,go!,Ottawa,poem</itunes:keywords>
		<itunes:subtitle>It's Poetry Friday and, since I've been pushed beyond my limits by members of the book industry's dark side, we present a poem I wrote back in the spring of 2005 to lament the loss of CBC Ottawa's much loved afternoon host, Brent Bambury. - </itunes:subtitle>
		<itunes:summary>It's Poetry Friday and, since I've been pushed beyond my limits by members of the book industry's dark side, we present a poem I wrote back in the spring of 2005 to lament the loss of CBC Ottawa's much loved afternoon host, Brent Bambury.

I've loved doing Just One More Book!! and it will be sad to turn my back on it.

While I'm reflecting on the future of what has been a huge part of our family, every single day for more than three years, I thought it was appropriate to share this era-ending poem (read by its recipient, Brent Bambury).

A Capital Lament -- by Andrea Ross, May 2005.

That April day, infused by May, seemed clearly heaven sent,
The Gomery mess couldn't bug us less -- we're listening to Brent!
Big news from Rome, then Pow! our own calamitous event,
We'd lost our man, and thus began our Capital Lament.

In two aught two, when Brent was new, our cautious ears we lent,
But soon his pace, words, voice and taste led to enravishment.
Who know his stint would be a glint? That Go! would lead to went?
And we'd be left a town bereft, despite all blandishments.

Robert Fontaine, comedien, now who will he torment?
Will Lucy sob? Or grab the job? To whom will Laurence vent?
We're sure of this, we'll sorely miss our host omniloquent.
You're lane to fame is Hog Town's gain. Best luck and Thank you, Brent.

Read Mark's post about Just One More Book!! as a member of our family: The baby, the bathwater, or both?</itunes:summary>
