			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-1304" title="It's A Snap! George Eastman's First Photograph" src="http://www.justonemorebook.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/itsasnap2.gif" alt="" />Author: <a title="Monica Kulling" href="http://www.MonicaKulling.com/" target="_blank">Monica Kulling</a> (<a title="Monica Kulling on JOMB" href="http://www.justonemorebook.com/?s=%22Monica%20Kulling%22">on JOMB</a>)<br />
Illustrator: Bill Slavin<br />
Published: 2009 <a title="more information/purchasing options at Tundra Books" href="http://www.tundrabooks.com/catalog/display.pperl?isbn=9780887768811" target="_blank">Tundra Books</a> (<a title="Tundra Books on JOMB" href="http://www.justonemorebook.com/?s=%22Tundra%20Books%22">on JOMB</a>)<br />
ISBN: 9780887768811</p>
<p>Rome wasn&#8217;t built in a day and neither was the compact camera. This sprightly tale of curiosity and determination puts the spotlight on the inventive young man who made photographers of all of us, one improvement at a time.</p>
<p><em>On this date, <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1888-09-04"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="09-04">September 4</span>, in 1888</span>, George Eastman registered the trademark <strong>Kodak</strong>. You can learn more <a title="The History of Kodak" href="http://www.kodak.com/US/en/corp/kodakHistory/eastmanTheMan.shtml" target="_blank">here</a>.</em></p>
